Django Advanced Regular Exam
Individual Project
Project Requirements for Django Advanced Course @ SoftUni
Your project is an opportunity to demonstrate your understanding of advanced Django concepts and RESTful API development by building a functional, visually appealing, and production-ready web application. You are expected to apply everything you have learned - from designing models, serializers, and class-based views to creating dynamic templates and maintaining clean, modular code. The project should showcase your ability to design, implement, and deploy a real-world solution independently, following Django's best practices and conventions. Focus on building a cohesive, original concept that reflects both technical proficiency and thoughtful architectural design.
1.	Project Requirements
Important Notes:
•	The submitted project must be downloadable, installable, and runnable without modifications. After installing dependencies and applying migrations, the application should start successfully using the default configuration.
•	All environment variables and credentials required for local testing must be clearly documented in your README file.

Core Functional Requirements
•	Your application must include both a public section (accessible to anonymous users) and a private section (accessible only to authenticated users).
o	The application must support user registration, login, and logout functionality.
•	There must be at least two user groups defined in the admin site, each with distinct permissions.
•	The built-in Django User model must be extended.
Technical Stack
•	The application must be implemented using Django and/or Django REST Framework (latest stable versions).
o	Your project must consist of at least five (5) Django apps, each with clearly defined responsibilities.
o	The application must define at least five (5) database models.
	Models created via inheritance or one-to-one relationships count as one model (e.g., User <-> Profile).
	Your database architecture must include at least two many-to-one and two many-to-many relationships.
Forms and Validations
•	The application must include at least seven (7) forms with proper data validations.
o	Display user-friendly error messages for invalid input.
o	Implement validations in both models and forms, where appropriate.
o	Customize error messages, help texts, labels, and placeholders.
o	Include read-only or disabled fields in at least two forms.
o	Exclude unnecessary fields when rendering forms.
o	Provide a confirmation step before deleting any object.
Views and APIs
•	Implement views to handle business logic:
o	Use Class-Based Views (CBVs) as the main approach (approximately 90% CBVs).
o	Handle forms correctly (GET and POST methods, validation, saving).
o	Use redirects after successful create/update actions.
o	Implement at least one RESTful API endpoint or service using Django REST Framework.
	Use serializers, API views, and permissions appropriately.
Templates and Frontend
•	The application must include at least fifteen (15) web pages/templates built using the Django Template Engine or rendered by a front-end framework (React, Angular, etc.):
o	At least ten (10) of them must display dynamic data from the database.
o	Implement full CRUD functionality for at least three (3) models (manageable by owners).
o	Include pages that display all objects, filtered/sorted objects, and single-object details, user details, or profiles, etc.
o	Showcase built-in and custom template filters/tags.
o	Provide custom error pages (404, 500, etc.).
o	Use a base template (not included in the 15-count).
o	Apply template inheritance and reusable partial templates.
o	Ensure that navigation links connect all pages consistently, and every page includes a footer.
o	Display or hide links appropriately for anonymous/authenticated users.
o	Templates can be reused across different views when appropriate.
o	Implement a responsive web design using Bootstrap, an AI-generated layout, or a custom design.
•	All pages in the application must be accessible through navigation links.
o	Avoid "orphan" pages that can only be reached by typing a URL manually.
o	Ensure consistent navigation menus and footers across the site.
o	Failure to provide functional navigation will affect your score, as any inaccessible pages will not be counted or evaluated.
Additional Technical Requirements
•	Implement asynchronous task processing (e.g., Celery, RQ, or asyncio-based tasks).
•	Ensure application security and data protection:
o	Prevent SQL injection, XSS, CSRF, and parameter tampering.
o	Use environment variables for sensitive data (no hardcoded secrets).
•	Use a PostgreSQL or another relational Database System.
•	Store and serve media and static files properly.
•	Include tests for custom logic, views, and user-related functionality (minimum 15 tests).
•	Deploy the project on a cloud-based platform.
o	The functionality and overall behaviour of your project will be assessed primarily based on the deployed version.
o	Ensure that the deployed application is fully functional, synchronized with your GitHub repository, and accessible during the evaluation period.
•	Use GitHub as your version control platform.
o	Submit a public GitHub repository link.
o	There must be a minimum of 7 (seven) commits on 7 (seven) separate days.
Documentation and Code Quality
•	Provide clear project documentation:
o	A comprehensive GitHub README describing setup, dependencies, and deployment.
o	Include environment setup instructions and sample .env configuration.
•	Follow OOP and clean code principles:
o	Apply data encapsulation and proper exception handling.
o	Demonstrate inheritance, abstraction, and polymorphism where relevant.
o	Follow strong cohesion and loose coupling principles.
o	Maintain readable, well-formatted code with clear naming conventions.
Disclaimer
•	It is NOT permissible to use any of the following in your project:
o	Ideas, Models, HTML, CSS, or entire Django apps taken from workshops, exercises, or lectures/presentations.
o	HTML/CSS/JS from JS modules, or any other SoftUni-related courses.
o	AI-generated code (except for HTML/CSS layouts or documentation).
•	If your project is found to be over 60% AI-generated, it will be disqualified (0 points).
•	Focus on developing a unique and original concept that reflects your understanding.
o	Failure to do so will negatively affect your final grade.
2.	Submission Deadline
•	You must submit a GitHub repository link before 15:59 on 07 April 2026 using the submission button in the Regular Exam section, available from 31 March 2026.
•	You may continue improving your project after assessment (after 16 April 2026)
o	Do not push new commits until evaluation is complete; work locally until then.
•	Projects not submitted by the deadline will NOT be evaluated.
•	The assessment is performed manually and typically takes up to 10 days.
3.	Assessment Criteria
•	Originality and Concept (unique idea, relevance, creativity) - maximum 10 points
•	Database Design and Relationships (model structure, M2M, FKs, constraints, fields, methods, Meta, query usage) - maximum 5 points
•	User Model extension, Groups/Permissions, Authentication - maximum 5 points
•	Forms, Validation, Media files handling - maximum 5 points
•	Views Implementation (90% CBVs, mixins, advanced techniques) - maximum 10 points
•	Pages (design, navigation, dynamic data) - maximum 10 points
•	Asynchronous Processing (task queues, scheduling, background jobs)- maximum 10 points
•	RESTful APIs (serializers, permissions, integration) - maximum 10 points
•	Deployment and Environment Configuration - maximum 10 points
•	Tests (coverage, correctness, relevance, minimum 15 tests) - maximum 5 points
•	Security and Data protection, Advanced Features and Functionality (not demonstrated by lecturer) - maximum 10 points
•	Project Documentation (README clarity, setup instructions, structure overview) - maximum 4 points
•	Version Control (Git discipline: commits, structure, descriptive messages) - maximum 3 points
•	Code Quality and Architecture (readability, OOP, structure) - maximum 3 points
